    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nWhen using padding in a `statuscolumn` string it appears that the calculation of terminal line width is incorrect and leads to incorrect wrapping/truncation of lines after line 100. It appears to be a large issue when there are multiple spaces in padding. (notice the missing `5` in the screenshot)\r\n\r\n![2023-10-02_10:17:29_screenshot](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/1591837/1dc232f7-b0e3-4634-b280-c89f99fe9aec)\r\n\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\nOpen a clean neovim sessions, set up the `statuscolumn` with multiple padding (this also works simply with `vim.opt.statuscolumn=\"  \"`/`vim.opt.statuscolumn=\"%l  \"`/etc.), then open a terminal and echo to see truncation/wrapping messes up\r\n\r\n```\r\nnvim --clean\r\n:lua vim.opt.statuscolumn=\"%C %l \"\r\n:set number\r\n:set foldcolumn=1\r\n:term\r\ni\r\nfor i in $(seq 100); do echo; done; echo\r\nfor i in $(seq 100); do echo -n 1234567890; done; echo\r\n```\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nThe terminal lines should be truncated/wrapped correctly and not lose characters.\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\n0.9.2 release\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nnot applicable since `statuscolumn` is a neovim feature\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nArch Linux\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nkitty 0.29.2\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-kitty\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\n`pacman -S nvim`",
